Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Per Order of Presiding Judge, Felony Division, this request/motion is hereby assigned to the Hon. Dennis R. Cimpl, Br. 19, for review. jbs
Motion for Modification of Conditions of Confinement

Defendant Orlando L. Washington in court with attorney Craig S. Powell.  Joshua Miles Mathy appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, Defense and Defendant.   Additional statement made by Kelly K.  The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 6 YEARS.  INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 3 YEARS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 3 YEARS.  Court STAYED sentence and placed the defendant on PROBATION for a period of 5 YEARS with the following conditions for probation and extended supervision:
Defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and is not eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.  
-Restitution set at $199,277.18  payable to Supplement Warehouse/Bankruptcy receiver Michael Polsky, to be collected during term of probation; $10,000.00 payable to Acuity Insurance Company, joint/several with Cory Hayes, 15CF1295.   Defendant informs the Court that he currently has $5,000.00 to pay towards restitution.  Defendant to pay this money either with the probation/parole department or through trust account of Attorney Craig Powell.  If defendant is revoked, restitution to be collected by DOC from the defendant's wages and from other monies held in the defendant's inmate account; an amount or a percentage which the department determines is reasonable for restitution to victims; nonpayment penalty shall be a civil judgment 
-Court WAIVED Court costs and all applicable assessments as defendant has a large amount of restitution to be paid 
-Defendant is to provide a DNA sample and pay the related surcharge, to be collected during term of probation. If defendant is revoked, all related surcharges are to be collected by DOC up to 25%  from the defendant's funds held in the defendant's inmate account; nonpayment penalty shall result in a civil judgment
-No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
-Cooperate with agent
-Cooperate with any correctional programs recommended
-Follow all rules of probation and extended supervision
-Pay all supervision fees 
-Obtain/maintain full-time employment 
-No contact with Robert L., Kelly K., Supplement Warehouse management team, Corey Hayes, Aaron M., Matthew M., 
-AODA assessment and any recommended treatment
-Random urine screens if department deems necessary 
-No illegal drugs 
-No use of prescription medications without a valid prescription
-Court has no objection to having probation transferred to the State of Colorado
-Court allows for travel permits to Colorado during term of probation
-As a condition of probation, Court ordered defendant serve 9 MONTHS in the House of Corrections, with Huber release privileges for work.  No good time credit.  Court does not object to electronic monitoring.  Defendant to report to the House of Corrections on June 27, 2017 by 5:00 p.m.

Defendant Orlando L. Washington in court with attorney Craig S. Powell.  Joshua Miles Mathy appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant changes plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon he may no longer use or possess any firearms; also he may not vote in any election until his civil rights have been restored.  Court further advised that if he is not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for April 27, 2017 at 01:30 pm.
